Professor '''Abdulaziz Al-Saqqaf''' (1952&ndash;1999) was a [[Yemen]]i [[human-rights]] activist, [[Economics|economist]], and [[journalist]]. <!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:saqqaf2.jpg|left|250px|thumb| Dr. Abdulaziz Al-Saqqaf while receiving the freedom press award, 1995 {{deletable image-caption}}]] --> Al-Saqqaf established the ''[[Yemen Times]]'', unified Yemenâs first and most widely-read [[English language|English-language]] independent [[newspaper]], in 1991, and was the winner of the N.P.C.'s ''International Award for Freedom of the Press'' for 1995. He was also a leading economist at the state-owned [[Sana'a University]]. He won the lifetime Achievement Award of the 2006 Middle East Publishing Conference in recognition of his efforts in promoting [[freedom of the press]] in Yemen and in the region. Dr. Al-Saqqaf was killed in 1999 when he was hit by a car.
Dr. Al-Saqqaf earned his doctoral degree in 1979 from the [[Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy]], Medford, Massachusetts.
